<br>
Armor: Warders get leather, Friars get cloth<br>
Spec points: Wardens Get 1.5, Friars get single points<br>
Races: 2 can be Wardens, Celts and Firbolg, Friars can only be Britons<br>
Weaponry: Wardens have blunt and blades, Friars have staves<br>
Rez: L10, both classes<br>
<br>
Those are the main differences. Wardens make excellent generalists, while a Friar is more specifically focused. To me it seems like Hyb has more class combinations that can overlap the Warden, while Friars are one of the only 2 clerical classes in Albion, ensuring an easier time finding a group. The single weapon style can actually be a blessing for the Friars, as there's no temptation to spread your points thin on another skill. <br>
<br>
Both are excelent classes, IMO, and have a great deal of potential for several different styles of play. <br>
<br>
Best advice was given earlier though. Play them both. You'll soon find what you like about each, and it's only a few hours invstment. Someone here (Was it Zad? I can't remember) played 4 Friars before making the one they're playing now. <br>
<br>
I've got several level 5-7 alts that I'm still experimenting with to see what I like about different classes in different realms.<br>
<br>
